    "key_notes": "Tunisia enter this match in crisis after a humiliating 5-1 opening loss to Sweden, sitting bottom of Group F. Hervé Renard was appointed in an emergency managerial change, replacing Sabri Lamouchi just days before this match — his debut as Tunisia coach and his fourth World Cup with a fourth different nation. Renard's pre-match message focused entirely on collective unity and defensive discipline: 'Against this Japanese team, we have to be perfect collectively.'\n\nFormation shift: Renard abandons Lamouchi's 3-5-2 for a compact 4-2-3-1 designed to deny Japan space in transition. The double pivot of Skhiri–Khedira screens a back four of Valery, Rekik, Talbi, and Abdi. Hannibal Mejbri operates as the free number 10 with license to roam. Elias Achouri and Ismaël Gharbi provide width. Firas Chaouat leads the line — he is Tunisia's leading international scorer in the squad with 6 goals in 28 caps.\n\nKey individual context: Skhiri (captain, Eintracht Frankfurt) made a costly error vs Sweden that led directly to a goal; he publicly stated he will 'bounce back' — high motivation but carrying psychological burden. Khedira received a 5.7 FotMob rating vs Sweden and a yellow card; contract at Union Berlin expires June 30, 2026, adding external pressure. Goalkeeper Dahmen (CS Sfaxien) replaces the error-prone Chamakh who directly contributed to the 1st and 3rd Swedish goals. Omar Rekik scored Tunisia's only goal in the 5-1 loss (header from Hannibal cross at 43') — his most notable contribution. Montassar Talbi is Tunisia's most experienced CB (49 caps) with aerial dominance as his main strength. Hannibal (Burnley, 23yo) was rated Tunisia's best individual performer vs Sweden despite the result; emotional_state is elevated as Renard specifically cited him for his creative personality. Ismaël Gharbi (22yo, on loan at Augsburg from Braga) has limited senior Tunisia experience (5 caps before the tournament) and very limited Bundesliga minutes this season (88'), adding to high composure_volatility. Ali Abdi (Nice, 32yo) is the oldest outfield starter; his red card in Ligue 1 this season signals discipline risk. Firas Chaouat plays in the Tunisian domestic league (Club Africain) — 15 goals in 2025-26 club season but faces a significant quality step up at this level.\n\nContextual state today: The new-manager effect typically elevates motivation and emotional state by 10-15 points across the squad. Tunisia are playing for survival — a loss effectively eliminates them. The Estadio BBVA in Monterrey is neutral ground in extreme heat (~35°C), which compounds stamina concerns. Japan lost Kubo to injury but remain technically superior; Tunisia must execute Renard's defensive block perfectly. No new injuries or suspensions reported in Tunisia's camp since the Sweden match."
